value.value: A non-neoplastic disorder that affects the structures of the mediastinum.  Representative examples include mediastinitis and thymic hyperplasia.
A non-neoplastic disorder that affects the heart and/or vessels.  Representative examples include myocardial infarction, endocarditis, arteriosclerosis, thrombosis, and lymphedema.
A malignancy in which there is a well-documented association between a neoplastic process and a specific virus as the causative agent.
A carcinoma associated with the presence of human papillomavirus infection.
A carcinoma that arises from the cervix and is caused by human papillomavirus infection.

label.value: Human Papillomavirus-Related Cervical Squamous Cell Carcinoma

value.value: A cervical squamous cell carcinoma associated with human papillomavirus infection.
A cervical adenocarcinoma associated with the presence of human papillomavirus infection.
A verrucous carcinoma that is associated with human papillomavirus infection.

label.value: Human Papillomavirus-Related Vulvar Squamous Cell Carcinoma

value.value: A squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the vulva and is caused by human papillomavirus infection.

A synthetic peptide vaccine consisting of the amino acids 44 through 59 of the glycoprotein 100 (gp100) melanoma antigen.  Vaccination with gp100_44-59 may stimulate the host immune system to mount a cytotoxic T lymphocyte (CTL) response against tumor cells positive for gp100, resulting in decreased tumor growth. (NCI04)

label.value: Human Papillomavirus-Related Esophageal Squamous Cell Carcinoma

value.value: An esophageal squamous cell carcinoma that arises from squamous epithelial cells infected with human papillomavirus.

label.value: Human Papillomavirus-Related Anal Squamous Cell Carcinoma

value.value: An anal squamous cell carcinoma related to infection with sexually transmittable human papillomavirus.

label.value: Penile Human Papillomavirus-Related Squamous Cell Carcinoma

value.value: A squamous cell carcinoma that arises from the penis and is caused by human papillomavirus infection.
A squamous cell carcinoma associated with the presence of human papillomavirus infection.
An adenocarcinoma associated with the presence of human papillomavirus infection.
A hepatocellular carcinoma that develops following hepatitis virus exposure and injury of the liver parenchyma.
A hepatocellular carcinoma that develops following hepatitis B virus exposure and injury of the liver parenchyma.
A hepatocellular carcinoma that develops following hepatitis C virus exposure and injury of the liver parenchyma.

A malignant neoplasm that develops in a patient infected with Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) and in which there is a well-documented association between the malignancy and EBV. Representative examples include EBV-related lymphomas and carcinomas.
Carcinoma that develops in individuals infected with Epstein-Barr virus (EBV), and in which there is a well-documented association between the neoplastic process and EBV.
Lymphoma that is caused by Epstein-Barr virus infection.
Hodgkin lymphoma that is caused by Epstein-Barr virus infection.
Non-Hodgkin lymphoma that is caused by Epstein-Barr virus infection.
Burkitt lymphoma that is caused by Epstein-Barr virus infection.
A clonal lymphoproliferative disorder that develops following organ transplantation and is associated with Epstein-Barr virus infection.
A lymphoproliferative disorder that develops following organ transplantation and is associated with Epstein-Barr virus infection.
Carcinoma that develops in the context of an individual infected with a virus.
Lymphoma that is caused by a virus infection.
A pharmacological agent that can kill or prevent the reproduction of parasitic protozoans.
Carcinoma occurring in HIV-positive patients.
Myelofibrosis that develops in patients with a history of hematologic malignancies or toxic injury to the bone marrow.
A myelodysplastic syndrome for which a patient has received treatment in the past.
A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to the translocation of the MYC gene to a new chromosomal location.
A sarcoma that is caused by a virus.

A chimeric lymphoma vaccine generated by combining the recipient's Ig idiotype (Id) protein with keyhole limpet hemocyanin (KLH), an immune stimulant, with potential antineoplastic activity.  Vaccination with KLH-Lymphoma Ig Vaccine may stimulate the host immune system to mount a cytotoxic T lymphocyte (CTL) response against lymphoma cells, resulting in decreased tumor growth. (NCI04)
A neoplasm originating from the apical lung. Most superior sulcus neoplasms are bronchogenic carcinomas. This tumor may be associated with Pancoast syndrome. It is also known as Pancoast tumor.

A cytogenetic abnormality that refers to loss of all or part of the long arm of chromosome 5 (5q). It is associated with the development of myelodysplastic syndrome with isolated deletion (5q), acute myeloid leukemia with multilineage dysplasia, and acute myeloid leukemia with myelodysplasia-related changes.
A molecular abnormality indicating rearrangement of the CCND1 gene in clonal populations of either lymphocytes or lymphocyte lineage neoplastic cells.
A chromosomal abnormality consisting of the translocation of 19p13.3 with 1q23, resulting in the fusion of the TCF3 (E2A) gene with the PBX1 gene.
A rare gastrointestinal stromal tumor that presents as a solitary mass outside the gastrointestinal tract.
